Here's the cleanest solution - add an endpoint to expose which social providers are configured, then conditionally render the buttons in the UI:

**1. Add API endpoint to return available providers:**

Add this in `apps/api/src/index.ts` after the `/api/cli-token` handler (around line 120):

```typescript
if (url.pathname === "/api/auth/providers") {
	return new Response(
		JSON.stringify({
			providers: Object.keys(socialProviders),
		}),
		{
			status: 200,
			headers: { ...cors, "Content-Type": "application/json" },
		},
	);
}
```

**2. Update the login form to fetch and conditionally render:**

In `apps/web/src/components/auth/login-form.tsx`, add state to track available providers and fetch them on mount:

```typescript
const [availableProviders, setAvailableProviders] = useState<string[]>([]);

useEffect(() => {
	fetch("/api/auth/providers")
		.then(r => r.json())
		.then(data => setAvailableProviders(data.providers))
		.catch(() => setAvailableProviders([]));
}, []);
```

Then conditionally render the social buttons section:

```typescript
{availableProviders.length > 0 && (
	<>
		<div className="flex items-center gap-2">
			<Separator className="flex-1" />
			<span className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">OR</span>
			<Separator className="flex-1" />
		</div>

		<div className="flex flex-col gap-2">
			{availableProviders.includes("google") && (
				<Button variant="outline" onClick={() => handleSocialSignIn("google")}>
					Continue with Google
				</Button>
			)}
			{availableProviders.includes("github") && (
				<Button variant="outline" onClick={() => handleSocialSignIn("github")}>
					Continue with GitHub
				</Button>
			)}
		</div>
	</>
)}
```

---

### **Option B: Quick fix - Just add OAuth credentials**

If you want to test social login in local dev, create test OAuth apps:

**For GitHub:**
1. Go to https://github.com/settings/developers
2. New OAuth App → Homepage URL: `http://localhost:4010`, Callback: `http://localhost:4010/api/auth/callback/github`
3. Add to `scripts/dev-local.sh`:
   ```bash
   export GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=your_client_id
   export GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=your_client_secret
   ```

**For Google:**
Similar process at https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials

---

Which approach do you prefer? **Option A is better for open source** since contributors won't need OAuth setup.

